*Update:* It seems hdmi driver requires handling for 2 interrupts index 0 and 1, but only interrupt 0 is defined in DTS (Device Tree Source), which shows the error log *_“kernel: dwhdmi-rockchip ff940000.hdmi: IRQ index 1 not found”_*. In additional, interrupt index 1 seems not a primary IRQ, hence the issue only happens rarely at boot time for some timing/glitch cases.

{noformat}//cstp-msi-rockchip-kernel-5.10.198-rk3399-linux-16/cstp-msi-rockchip-kernel-5.10.198-rk3399-linux-16/arch/arm64/boot/dts/rockchip/rk3399.dtsi
    hdmi: hdmi@ff940000 {
		compatible = "rockchip,rk3399-dw-hdmi";
		reg = <0x0 0xff940000 0x0 0x20000>;
		interrupts = <GIC_SPI 23 IRQ_TYPE_LEVEL_HIGH 0>;
        ...
    }{noformat}

{color:#4c9aff}*Next step:*{color} List down some *CEC wake up* use case of *CX-M Taishan* to see if the issue can be reproduced manually.

*Update:* The issue might relate to *CEC wake up feature* (Consumer Electronics Control) on a *CX-M Taishan* at *boot time* due to below hint:

# DTS (Device Tree Source) for {{hdmi@ff940000}} only defines 1 interrupt index 0, but the hdmi driver requires handling of 2 interrupt index (0 and 1). And interrupt index 1 refers to CEC feature:
{code:c++}//cstp-msi-rockchip-kernel-5.10.198-rk3399-linux-16\cstp-msi-rockchip-kernel-5.10.198-rk3399-linux-16\drivers\gpu\drm\bridge\synopsys\dw-hdmi.c
struct dw_hdmi *dw_hdmi_probe(struct platform_device *pdev,
			      const struct dw_hdmi_plat_data *plat_data)
{
    //...
    if (config0 & HDMI_CONFIG0_CEC) {
		cec.hdmi = hdmi;
		cec.ops = &dw_hdmi_cec_ops;
		cec.irq = irq;

		irq = platform_get_irq(pdev, 1);          // error log here: IRQ index 1 not found
		if (irq < 0)
			dev_dbg(hdmi->dev, "can't get cec wake up irq\n");

		cec.wake_irq = irq;

		pdevinfo.name = "dw-hdmi-cec";
		pdevinfo.data = &cec;
		pdevinfo.size_data = sizeof(cec);
		pdevinfo.dma_mask = 0;

		hdmi->cec = platform_device_register_full(&pdevinfo);
	}{code}

