A policy file test.pol was made with content:

{noformat}entry one {
    if match any {
       nlri 224.2.127.254/32;
     } then {
       permit;
     }
}{noformat}

and applied. But for completeness I add a summary of the steps taken:

# First check the current policy configurations:
{noformat}show config mcmgr{noformat}

in which you look for something like `config igmp snooping flood-list test`.

# In the case when no snooping policy is configured, check the number of IPMC caches via (5120 limit is ~192 with max of 256):
{noformat}debug hal show ipv4mc{noformat}
# Check whether the logging is in debug-mode and the cache misses are logged by looking in the `# Module ems configuration.` section of the configuration file. So show the configuration file:
{noformat}show configuration{noformat}
and look for the following excerpt, and when not available add it:
{noformat}#
# Module ems configuration.
#
enable log debug-mode
configure log filter DefaultFilter add events IPMC.Snoop.l3CacheMiss 
configure log filter DefaultFilter add events IPMC.Snoop.l2CacheMiss {noformat}
# Check for resource exceeded logs:
{noformat}show logs{noformat}
# So, if the policy is NOT configured AND they are hitting L3 table exceeded OR cache misses, we can apply a similar policy (test is the test.pol file being applied):
{noformat}config igmp snooping flood-list test{noformat}
# After applying the policy, we’ll want them to issue:
{noformat}clear igmp snooping{noformat}
# And then monitor the log.
And run
{noformat}debug hal show ipv4mc{noformat}
to look for IPMC cache limits.

